07208nam a22014295i 9781400880973DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984662407  a97814008809737 a10.1515/97814008809732doi  a(DE-B1597)468050  a(OCoLC)945697843  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC574.2.U6bS35 2018 7aPOL0040002bisacsh04a320.513097309042231 aSchickler, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRacial Realignment :bThe Transformation of American Liberalism, 1932-1965 /cEric Schickler. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b34 line illus. 1 table.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in American Politics: Historical, International, and Comparative Perspectives ;v15300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tPart 1. Transforming American Liberalism -- tChapter 2. Race -- tChapter 3. Transforming Liberalism, 1933-1940 -- tChapter 4. Liberalism Transformed -- tPart 2. Realignment From Below: Voters And Midlevel Party Actors -- tChapter 5. Civil Rights and New Deal Liberalism in the Mass Public -- tChapter 6. The African American Realignment and New Deal Liberalism -- tChapter 7. State Parties and the Civil Rights Realignment -- tChapter 8. Beyond the Roll Call -- tPart 3. The National Parties Respond -- tChapter 9. Facing A Changing Party -- tChapter 10. Lincoln's Party No More -- tChapter 11. Conclusions -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew transformations in American politics have been as important as the integration of African Americans into the Democratic Party and the Republican embrace of racial policy conservatism. The story of this partisan realignment on race is often told as one in which political elites-such as Lyndon Johnson and Barry Goldwater-set in motion a dramatic and sudden reshuffling of party positioning on racial issues during the 1960s. Racial Realignment instead argues that top party leaders were actually among the last to move, and that their choices were dictated by changes that had already occurred beneath them. Drawing upon rich data sources and original historical research, Eric Schickler shows that the two parties' transformation on civil rights took place gradually over decades.Schickler reveals that Democratic partisanship, economic liberalism, and support for civil rights had crystallized in public opinion, state parties, and Congress by the mid-1940s. This trend was propelled forward by the incorporation of African Americans and the pro-civil-rights Congress of Industrial Organizations into the Democratic coalition. Meanwhile, Republican partisanship became aligned with economic and racial conservatism. Scrambling to maintain existing power bases, national party elites refused to acknowledge these changes for as long as they could, but the civil rights movement finally forced them to choose where their respective parties would stand.Presenting original ideas about political change, Racial Realignment sheds new light on twentieth and twenty-first century racial politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rightszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiberalismzUnited States. 0aRacismxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh  aAfrican American movement.  aAfrican American population.  aAfrican American voters.  aAfrican Americans.  aAl Smith.  aAmerican politics.  aCongress of Industrial Organizations.  aCongress.  